definition.value: An organic cation obtained by protonation of the anilino function of tricaine.
An S-substituted N-acetyl-L-cysteine that is the thioester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of glyceric acid with the thiol group of N-acetyl-L-cysteine.
A monounsaturated fatty acid aldehyde that is undec-10-enal substituted at position 2 by a methyl group.
A secondary alcohol that is ethanol in which one of the hydrogens at position 1 has been replaced by a cyclopentyl group.
A member of the class of triazoles that is 2H-1,2,3-triazole carrying two phenyl substituents at positions 4 and 5.
A 1-monoglyceride in which the acyl group is specified as (9E)-octadecenoyl.
A naphthoate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 1-naphthoic acid with the phenolic hydroxy group of 4-nitrophenol.
An alkenyl alcohol that is 1-undecene in which one of the terminal methyl hydrogens is replaced by a hydroxy group.

A pentasubstituted dihydropyridine carrying methoxycarbonyl, 2-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl and nitro substituents at positions 3, 4 and 5 respectively as well as two methyl substituents at positions 2 and 6.
A phenol that is bisphenol A in which one of the phenolic hydrogens has been replaced by a methyl group.
A methyl 2,6-dimethyl-5-nitro-4-[2-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]-1,4-dihydropyridine-3-carboxylate in which the 4-position has (S)-configuration.
A polyphenol consisting of propane in which both methylene hydrogens at position 2 have been replaced by 2-hydroxyphenyl groups.
A methyl 2,6-dimethyl-5-nitro-4-[2-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]-1,4-dihydropyridine-3-carboxylate in which the 4-position has (R)-configuration.
A hydroxyaldehyde that is pentanal carrying three hydroxy substituents at positions 3, 4 and 5.

A member of the class of triazoloquinazolines that is [1,2,4]triazolo[1,5-c]quinazoline substited at positions 2, 5 and 9 by furan-2-yl, amino and chloro groups respectively. A potent antagonist at adenosine A1 and adenosine A2A receptors.
Any deoxyhexose existing in the pyranose form and lacking a hydroxy group at position 2.
A 3-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is pentanoic acid substituted at positions 2 and 3 by ethyl and oxo substituents respectively.
A 3-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is butyric acid substituted at positions 2 and 3 by ethyl and hydroxy groups respectively.
An organic heterotricyclic compound that consists of a triazole ring ortho-fused at any position to a quinazoline ring system.
A monocarboxylic acid that is 4-methylpentanoic acid in which both methylene hydrogens at positions 2 have been replaced by a hydroxyimino (the E-geoisomer).
A  glycol that is 1,2-butanediol carrying an additional methyl substituent at position 2.

A member of the class of cyanopyridines that is 6-amino-3,5-dicyano-4-(4-hydroxyphenyl)-2-sulfanylpyridine in which the hydroxy and sulfanyl hydrogens are replaced by cyclopropylmethyl and carboxamidomethyl groups respectively.
An agonist at the A2B receptor.
A glycol that is cumene carrying two hydroxy substituents at positions 1 and 2
A hydrate that is the pentahydrate form of disodium selenite.
A sulfonate ester obtained by formal condensation of one of the hydroxy groups of ethylene glycol with sulfonic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid that is dec-2-enedioic acid substituted at position 3 by a hydroxy group (the Z-geoisomer).
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is pentanoic acid carrying three carboxy substituents at positions 2, 3 and 4.
A hydrate that is the decahydrate form of disodium tetraborate.
A 3-hydroxymonocarboxylic acid that is the 3-hydroxy derivative of 3-butenoic acid.
A glycol that is 1,4-butanediol substituted at position 2 by a methylidene group.
An acetylenic compound that is 5-nonyne carrying a hydroxy substituent at position 3.
An enone that is 3-penten-2-one carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 4.
An inorganic phosphate having Fe(3+) as the counterion.
A hydrate that is the tetrahydrate form of iron(3+) phosphate.
A member of the class of chromenes that is 7,7-dimethyl-5-oxo-5,6,7,8-tetrahydrochromene carrying additional amino, cyano and 3-cyclohexen-1-yl substituents at positions 2, 3 and 4 respectively.
An oxime ether that is 3,6-bis(methoxyimino)hexane carrying four hydroxy substituents at positions 1, 2, 4 and 5.
An aromatic alcohol that is (but-3-en-1-yl)benzene in which one of the benzylic methylene hydrogens has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A ketoxime derived from 5-methylhexan-2-one.
An acetate ester derived from (8Z)-7-methyl-8-tetradecen-1-ol.
A hydrate that is the heptahydrate form of ferrous ammonium sulfate.
A 2-monoglyceride in which the acyl group is specified as (9E,12E,15E)-octadecatrienoyl.
A 2-monoglyceride in which the acyl group is specified as (9E)-9-octadecenoyl.
A tetradecenoic acid that is the E-geoisomer of tetradec-9-enoic acid.
A branched alkane that is nonane carrying seven methyl substituents at positions 2, 2, 4, 4, 6, 8 and 8.
A tetrol that is hexane-1,2,3,4-tetrol carrying two methoxy substituents at both position 5 and position 6.
A ketoxime obtained by condensation of the keto group of 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic acid with hydroxylamine.
A ketoxime obtained by condensation of the keto group of phenylpyruvic acid with hydroxylamine.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of iron(3+) sulfate.
